   <mods:abstract>This dissertation contends that scholars should incorporate a concern for the suffering of those most vulnerable as a criterion for evaluating the merits of works of theological ethics. It does so by considering four case studies in which works of Christian theology and ethics are evaluated using this criterion within their sociohistorical, traditional, and philosophical contexts. It contends that each of these four positions possess lacunae that could have been avoided by a closer attention to the lived experiences of vulnerable people, especially the poor, women, BIPOC individuals, and LGBTQ+ individuals. This dissertation serves as a work of liberation theology that asks ethicists, scholars of religion, and theologians alike to attend to the material impacts of their work upon vulnerable communities and to treat these communities, ultimately, as theologically innovative and as sources for theological and moral reflection.</mods:abstract>
